SOCIAL AND CULTURAL AWAKENING

‚Ä¢ The growth of the modern middle class in India was the result of a two fold process ‚Äì the destruction of the old class on the one hand, and the rise of new groups of landholders, businessmen and intellectuals on the other.

‚Ä¢ The modern Indian middle class made its first appearance in the newly founded cities of Madras, Bombay and Calcutta, and in the towns which became the subsidiary centres of British commercial activity and administration.

‚Ä¢ The combined economic and political changes laid the foundation for the unity of Indian people.

‚Ä¢ The different regions of India were brought nearer to one another by the extension of the means of communication ‚Äì roads, railways, posts and telegraph.

Causes of the Social and Cultural Awakening

‚Ä¢ The first and foremost was the establishment of British rule, which created conditions favourable to intellectual growth.

‚Ä¢ A second contributory factor was the pain staking efforts of the orientalists to bring into the limelight India‚Äôs past.

‚Ä¢ A third factor in the spread of the reform movement was the highly creative literature, which was marked by a marvellous fusion of the old and the new, a grand intermingling of the best literary traditions of ancient India with the good features of the culture of the modern world outside.

‚Ä¢ The fourth factor was the detrimental effect of the Christian missionaries.

Reform Movements

‚Ä¢ The earliest expression of reforms was in Bengal, initiated by Raja Ram Mohun Roy.

‚Ä¢ He founded the Atmiya Sabha in 1814, precursor of his Brahmo Samaj (1829).

‚Ä¢ Hinduism had the
o Paramahansa Mandali and Prarthana Samaj in Maharashtra
o Arya Samaj in the Punjab and other parts of North India;

‚Ä¢ The upper castes had
o Kayastha Sabha (UP)
o Sarin Sabha (Punjab)

‚Ä¢ The backward castes had
o Satya Shodhak Samaj (Maharashtra) and
o Sri Narayana Darma Paripalana Yogam (SNDPY, Kerala)

‚Ä¢ The Muslims had the Ahmadiya and Aligarh movements.

‚Ä¢ The Sikhs had the Singh Sabha.

‚Ä¢ The Parsis had Rahnumai Mazdeyasan Sabha.

‚Ä¢ Reforms movements may be broadly identified with 4 major trends in Indian society. These are:
1. Reforms from within.
2. Reform through legislation.
3. Reform through symbols of change.
4. Reform through social work.

‚Ä¢ Raja Ram Mohun Roy believed that the philosophy of Vedanta was based on the principle of reason.

‚Ä¢ Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar worked for the uplift of the status of Indian women.

o He waged a long struggle in favour of Hind widow remarriage, backing his advocacy with quotations from traditional Hindu religious texts.

o In 1856 Hindu Widow Remarriage Act was passed.

o His other contribution to Indian culture was evolving a technique of teaching Sanskrit and writing of a Bengali primer.

‚Ä¢ The advocates of ‚Äòreform through legislation‚Äô were Keshab Chandra Sen in Bengal, M.G. Ranade in Maharashtra, Veereshalingam in Andhra etc.

Reform through symbol of change

‚Ä¢ This was a manifestation of non-conformist individual activity, limited to the ‚ÄòDerozians‚Äô or ‚ÄòYoung Bengal‚Äô who represented a radical stream within the reform movement.

‚Ä¢ They were passionate advocates of women‚Äôs rights and demanded education for them.

‚Ä¢ Derozio attacked old and decadent customs, rites and traditions.

‚Ä¢ He was teacher at Hindu College from 1826 to 1831 and he was removed in 1831 because of his radicalism.

‚Ä¢ The prominent members of ‚ÄòYoung Bengal‚Äô were - Dakshinaranjan Mukherjee, Ram Gopal Ghose and Krishna Mohan Banerji.

Reform Through Social Work

‚Ä¢ Manifested in the activities of Dayananda Saraswathi‚Äôs Arya Samaj, Rama Krishna Mission, Swami Vivekananda and Prarthana Samaj in Maharashtra.

‚Ä¢ To Gopal Hari Deshmukh in Maharashtra, popularly known as Lokahithawadi, whether social reform had the sanction of religion or not was immaterial.

‚Ä¢ Arya Samaj, started by swami Dayand in 1875, preached not only the repudiation uof the caste system but the revival of Hindu society of the Vedic period based only on 4 castes.

‚Ä¢ Arya Samaj stood for extending the right to study the scriptures even to the lowest castes ‚Äì the Shudras.

‚Ä¢ The Arya Samaj stood for equal rights of men and women in social and educational matters.

‚Ä¢ The Arya Samaj organized a network of schools and colleges in the country. The DAV College was founded in 1886.

Raja Ram Mohun Roy and Brahmo Samaj

‚Ä¢ The first Indian who tried to pull the Indian society out of the medieval age.

‚Ä¢ His new ideas gave birth to Indian Renaissance.

‚Ä¢ He was a ‚Äúbridge between the past and future‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ He was called as the ‚ÄúFather of Modern India‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ Born in village Radhanagar, Hooghly District, Bengal on May 22, 1772 in an orthodox Brahmin family.

‚Ä¢ His father: Rama Kanth Roy.

‚Ä¢ His grandfather: Krishna Chandra Benerjee, whose title was Ray Rayan.

‚Ä¢ Ray Rayan title was later contracted into Roy.

‚Ä¢ Raja Ram Mohun Roy was a profound scholar of Arabic, Persian, Sanskrit, English, Bengali, Greek, latin and Hebrew.

‚Ä¢ He worked under the East India Company ‚Äì 1803 to 1814.
His literary works are:
Tuhfat-ul-Muwah-hidin (Gift to Monotheists), a treatise in Persian published in 1803
Manazarutul Aadyan a discussion in Persian on various religions
Translation of some parts of Vedanta and the Kena Upanishad.
Translation of Vedanta Sutras into English.

‚Ä¢ He published precepts of Jesus ‚Äì the guide to peace and happiness, which contained his conviction about the simplicity and morality of the Christian religion.

‚Ä¢ The turning point in his life was the performance of Sati by his elder brother‚Äôs wife in 1811.

‚Ä¢ In 1822, he published ‚ÄúModern Encroachments on the Ancient Rights of Females according to the Hindu law of Inheritance‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ As a result of his sustained efforts, the Governor General Lord William Bentinck passed Regulation XVII on Dec. 4, 1829 which declared Sati illegal.

‚Ä¢ He founded the Atmiya Sabha (1815‚Äì19).

‚Ä¢ In 1828, he established the Brahmo Sabha, later the Brahmo Samaj.

‚Ä¢ The Brahmo religion laid emphasis on the love of mankind.

‚Ä¢ He silently worked for the foundation of the Hindu college, Calcutta.

‚Ä¢ In Dec 1821 he launched a Bengali weekly, Sabad Kaumudi or ‚ÄúThe Moon of Intelligence‚Äù, which was the first Indian newspaper edited, published and managed by Indians.

‚Ä¢ In 1822, he began publication of another weekly in Persian ‚Äì Mirat-ul-Akhbar or ‚ÄúThe Mirror of Intelligence‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ In 1830, Raja Ram Mohun Roy went to England as an envoy of the Mughal Emperor, Akbar Shah II, who invested him with the title of Raja to the court of King William IV.

‚Ä¢ He died in England on Sept 27, 1833.

‚Ä¢ Maharshi Dwarakanath Tagore and the Pandit Ram Chandra Vidyavagish managed Brahma Samaj for about 10 years. Then a true leader was found in Devendranath Tagore, Dwarkanath‚Äôs eldest son.

‚Ä¢ Before joining the Brahmo Samaj, Devendranath Tagore organized the Tattvaranjini Sabha at Jorasanko (Calcutta), later renamed as Tattvabodhini sabha.

‚Ä¢ In 1840, the Tattvabodhini School was founded, where Akshay Kumar Dutta ‚Äì was appointed as a teacher. Its members were Pandit Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar, Rajendra Lal Mitra, Tara Chand Chakravarty, Peary Chand Mitra.

‚Ä¢ Tattvabodhini Sabha, published a monthly journal called Tattvabodhini Patrika.

‚Ä¢ Devendranath along with 20 of his associates formally joined the Brahmo Samaj on Dec 21, 1843.

‚Ä¢ He stood against the ultra radical trend of missionary attacks on Indian culture launched by Alaxendar Duff.

‚Ä¢ He compiled a religious text ‚ÄòBrahmo Dharma‚Äô.

‚Ä¢ He introduced the Brahmo form of worship or Brahmopasana.

Keshav Chandra Sen and Sangat Sabha

‚Ä¢ In Devendranath‚Äôs absence Keshav Chandra Sen joined in Brahmo Samaj in 1857 and became full-time missionary of the Samaj.

‚Ä¢ He established in 1859 a small society known as Sangat Sabha (‚ÄòFriendly Association‚Äô). Its main objective was to discuss the spiritual and social problems of the da.

‚Ä¢ Brahmo rites are mentioned in the Anushthana Paddhati.

‚Ä¢ In 1861, a fortnightly journal named as Indian mirror was started with Keshav Chandra Sen as editor. The Mirror had a distinguished career, becoming the first Indian daily paper in English.

‚Ä¢ As a result of Keshav Chandra Sen mission Ved Samaj was established in Madras and Prarthana Samaj in Maharashtra.







The First Schism

‚Ä¢ In the Brahmo Samaj in 1866, when Devendranath‚Äôs group, calling itself Adi Brahmo Samaj, separated from Keshav Chandra Sen‚Äôs group, which assumed the name of Brahmo Samaj of India or the New Dispensation or Convention (Nav Vidhana).

‚Ä¢ Slogan of Adi Brahmo Samaj was ‚ÄúBrahmoism is Hinduism‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ The slogan of Nav Vidhana was ‚ÄúBrahmoism is Catholic and Universal‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ In 1872, he persuaded the government to place on the statute book the Brahmo Marriage Act, which legalized marriage according to Brahmo rites.

‚Ä¢ Keshav Chandra Sen also established the Indian Reform Association.

Second Schism

‚Ä¢ Keshav Chandra Sen had his daughter married to Maharaja of Cooch‚ÄìBehar in 1878, both the bride and bridegroom being under-age. To boot, the marriage was conducted in accordance with Hindu rites and in violation of the Brahmo Marriage Act of 1872.

‚Ä¢ Keshav Chandra Sen died in 1884.

Sadharana Brahmo Samaj

‚Ä¢ The constitution of Sadharana Brahmo Samaj, drafted by Anand Moham Bose.
‚Ä¢ Important member‚Äôs:
ÔÇß Sivanth Sastri,
ÔÇß Anand Mohan Bose,
ÔÇß Bipan Chandra Pal,
ÔÇß Dwarak Nath Ganguly
ÔÇß Sir Surendra Nath Bennerjee.

