Young Bengal Movement

‚Ä¢ Owed its origin to a most remarkable personality of the 19th century ‚Äì Henry Louis Vivian Derozio who came to Calcutta in 1826 and was appointed in the Hindu college as a teacher of English literature and History.

‚Ä¢ He edited Hesperus and Calcutta Literary Gazette.

‚Ä¢ He was connected with Indian Gazette as well.

Prarthana Samaj

‚Ä¢ As a result of Keshav Chandra Sen‚Äôs visit to Maharashtra, the Prarthana Samaj (‚ÄòPrayer Society‚Äô) was founded in 1867.

‚Ä¢ Founder: M.G. Ranade, described as ‚Äúthe prophet of cultural renaissance in Western India‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ Other important leaders: Dr. Atmaram Panduranga and R.G.Bhandarkar.

‚Ä¢ The two main planks of the Samaj were worship and social reform.

‚Ä¢ M.G.Rande views regarding theism are set out in 39 articles which he drew up under the title ‚ÄúA Theist‚Äôs Confession of Faith‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ Two other champions of social reform with M.G.Ranade were Dhondo Keshav Karve and Vishnu Shastri.

‚Ä¢ Ranade and Karve launched the widow remarriage movement and started Widows‚Äô Home Association, to provide education to widows.

Jyotiba Phule and Satya Shodhak Samaj

‚Ä¢ He organized a powerful non-Brahmin movement.

‚Ä¢ Born in 1828 in a Mali family.

‚Ä¢ In 1854, he opened a school for the ‚Äòuntouchables‚Äô and started a private orphanage to help widows.

‚Ä¢ He founded the Satya Shodhak Samaj in 1873.

‚Ä¢ He wrote two critical works ‚Äì Sarvajanik Satyadharma Pustak and Ghulamgiri.



Veda Samaj

‚Ä¢ Keshav Chandra Sen during his visit to Madras in 1864 persuaded the people to establish the Veda Samaj.

‚Ä¢ Founder: K. Sridarulu Naidu.

‚Ä¢ He changed the Veda Samaj into the Brahmo Samaj of Southern India in 1871.

‚Ä¢ He translated the books of Brahmodharma into Tamil and Telugu.

Dayananda Saraswathi and Arya Samaj

‚Ä¢ Mula Shankar, later known as Dayanand Saraswathi, was born in 1824 in a Brahmin family, in the petty state of Morvi, in Kathiawar, Gujarat.

‚Ä¢ He spent two and a half years at Mathura as a disciple of a blind saint scholar Swami Virjananda.

‚Ä¢ He came to the conclusion that ‚ÄúAryans were chosen people, the Vedas the chosen gospel and India the chosen land.

‚Ä¢ He founded the Arya Samaj in Bombay in 1875. A few yeayrs later the headquarters of the Arya Samaj were established at Lahore.

‚Ä¢ He translated the Vedas.

‚Ä¢ He wrote three books;
1. Satyartha Prakash in Hindi.
2. Veda Bhasya Bhumika, an introduction to his vedic commentary.
3. Veda Bhasya, a Vedic commentary in Sanskrit on the Yajurvada and the major part of the Rig Veda.

‚Ä¢ It was very successful in the Punjab and to a certain degree also in UP, Gujarat and Rajasthan.

‚Ä¢ Dayanand Saraswati looked upon the Vedas as ‚ÄòIndia‚Äôs Rock of Ages‚Äô.

‚Ä¢ He gave the slogan ‚ÄòGo back to the Vedas‚Äô, and ‚Äòthe Vedas are the source of all knowledge‚Äô.

‚Ä¢ He rejected the authority of the later Hindu scriptures like the Puranas.

‚Ä¢ The Arya Samaj denounced the infinite number of meaningless rites, and the worship of the images of different gods and goddesses.

‚Ä¢ Arya Samaj stood for the fourfold Varna system to be determined by merit and not by birth.

‚Ä¢ It stood for equal rights of man and woman.

‚Ä¢ Activities of the Arya Samaj were very controversial.
ÔÇß Shuddhi Programme,
ÔÇß Programme for protection of the cow.

‚Ä¢ In 1882 the Arya Samaj formed a ‚ÄòCow Protection Association‚Äô.

Vivekananda and Ramakrishna Mission

‚Ä¢ The Rama Krishna monastic order and mission was officially established in 1887 (formally registered under Societies‚Äô Registration Act in 1909) by Vivekananda, the chief disciple of Swamy Ramakrishna Paramahansa of Dakshineshwar.

‚Ä¢ ‚ÄúThe only god in whom I believe, the sum total of all souls, and above all, my God the wicked, my God the afflicted, my God the poor of all races‚Äù ‚Äì Vivekananda.

‚Ä¢ In 1893, he went to America and attended the World Parliament of Religions at Chicago.

‚Ä¢ Vivekananda established two principal centres:
1. At Belur near Calcutta.
2. Mayavati near Almora, where the men trained as Sanyasis.

‚Ä¢ Vivekananda believed in the philosophy of Vedanta.

‚Ä¢ Vivekananda pamphlet, ‚ÄòI am a Socialist‚Äô.

‚Ä¢ The concept of Daridra-Narayana popularized by Gandhiji, had its origin in Vivekananda.

‚Ä¢ ‚ÄòIndian Unrest‚Äô book written by Valentine Chirol.

Theosophical Movement

‚Ä¢ The Theosophical Society was founded by Madame Blavatsky and Col. Olcott in New York in 1875.

‚Ä¢ The founders arrived in India in Jan 1897, and established the headquarters of the Society at Adyar near Madras.

‚Ä¢ In 1888, Mrs. Annie Besant joined the Society in England.

‚Ä¢ Theosophical Society opened the Central Hindu College at Varanasi in 1898.

‚Ä¢ This movement encouraged participation in the Boy Scout Movement.



Orthodox Hindu Societies

The Bharat Darma Mahamandala

‚Ä¢ It was an all India organisation; an apex body of various orthodax Hindu organisations.

‚Ä¢ Founded by Pandit Din Dayalu Sharma in Hardwar in 1887.

‚Ä¢ Objective: to bring together all leaders of the orthodox Hindu community and to work together for the preservation of Sanatan Dharma.

‚Ä¢ Pandit Din Dayalu founded the Hindu college, Delhi, on May 15, 1899.

‚Ä¢ The offshoots of the Mahamandala were the Sanatan Dharma Sabhas.

‚Ä¢ Pandit Madan Mohun Malavia was very closely associated with the Mahamandala and the Sanatan Dharma movements.

Dharma Sabha

‚Ä¢ Founder: Radhakant Deb. Year of Establishment: 1830.

Reformist Movements

The Veda Samaj

‚Ä¢ Founded in Madras in 1864 by K. Sridharulu Naidu.

‚Ä¢ Doraiswami Iyengar, openly talked of abandoning the sacred thread.




Swami Naryana Sect

‚Ä¢ Swami Sahajanand, founded this sect in Gujarat.

‚Ä¢ This sect was a sort of protest against the epicurean and luxurious practices of Vaishnavism.

‚Ä¢ This sect preached monotheism.

DAV Education Movement

‚Ä¢ First Dayananda Anglo-Vedic (DAV) School was opened in Lahore in 1886. Lala Hans Raj worked as honorary Principal.

‚Ä¢ In May 1889, the Punjab University granted affiliation to the DAV College.

‚Ä¢ By 1910, the DAV trust framed rules and regulations governing the schools affiliated to it.

‚Ä¢ Foundation of Arya Kanya Pathshala in Jullundar in 1890.

‚Ä¢ Foundation of Kanya Mahavidhyalaya (college) in 1896.

‚Ä¢ The Kanya Mahavidhyalaya published literature for women‚Äôs education and founded the Hindi monthly ‚ÄòPanchal Pandita‚Äô in 1898, to preach and propagate female education.

‚Ä¢ Lala Hasraj became the leader of the moderates, who came to be known as the ‚ÄúCollege Party‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ The leadership of the militants, later known as the ‚ÄúGurukul‚Äù wing, was centred around Pandit Lekh Ram and Lala Munshi Ram (later known as Swami Shraddhanand).

‚Ä¢ The Gurukul focused on Aryan ideology, the study of Sanskrit and the Vedic scriptures.

‚Ä¢ In 1893, the Arya Samaj formally broke up.

‚Ä¢ In March 1892, Lala Munshi Ram (Swamy Shraddhanand) founded the Gurukul Kangri in Hardwar.




The Shuddhi Movement

‚Ä¢ Militant Arya Samajists developed their own ritual of conversion called Shuddhi.

‚Ä¢ The Shuddi Sabha conducted reconversions during the 1880s and early 1890s.

‚Ä¢ In Dec 1923, eighty representatives from Hindu, Jain and Sikh caste associations agreed to form a new organisation ‚Äì the Bharatiya Hindu Shuddhi Sabha ‚Äì to work for the goal of reconversion.

Jat Pat Todak Mandal (Society for the Abolition of Caste)

‚Ä¢ It is founded in Lahore in 1922 by Bhai Paramand.

Sarvadeshik Hindu Sabha

‚Ä¢ Hindus founded the Punjab Hindu Conference in 1909.

‚Ä¢ In 1915, this conference renamed itself the Sarvadeshik Hindu Sabha and in 1921, the Akhil Bharat Hindu Mahasabha.

‚Ä¢ By the mid-1930s, the Mahasabha, under the leadership of V.D. Savarkar, began to expound a Hindu nationalism.

Radhaswami Movement

‚Ä¢ Founded in 1861 by Tulsi Ram, of Agra.

‚Ä¢ Tulasi Ram was also popularly known as Shiv Dayal Saheb or Swamiji Maharaj.

‚Ä¢ The Radhaswamis believe in one Supreme Being, the supremacy of the Guru, a ‚Äúcompany of pious people‚Äù (satsang).

‚Ä¢ The sect recognizes no temples, shrines or sacred places.

Deva Samaj

‚Ä¢ Founded in 1887 at Lahore by Shiv Narayan Agnihotri, an erstwhile follower of Brahmo Samaj.

‚Ä¢ The teachings of the Samaj were compiled in book form in Deva Shastra.

‚Ä¢ The movement lost its popular appeal after 1813, when Agnihotri appointed his second son, Devanand, as his successor.

Madras Hindu Associations

1. The Madras Hindu Social Reforms Association founded by Veresalingam Pantulu in 1892.
2. The Madras Hindu association founded by Mrs. Annie Besant in 1904.

Sathnamis of Chhattisgarh

‚Ä¢ Founder of Sathnami sect: Ghasi Das.

‚Ä¢ He propounded the concept of Satnam, a single true god, and urged his followers to abandon idol worship.

‚Ä¢ After Ghasi Das‚Äôs death in 1850, his son Balak Das took over the leadership of the Sathnamis.



The Satya Mahima Dharma

‚Ä¢ Mukund Das, known as Mahima Gosain founded this in 1860s, assisted mainly by Govind Baba and Bhima Bhoi.

‚Ä¢ Gosain preached the existence of one deity Alakh Param Brahma.

‚Ä¢ Idol worship was in vain.

‚Ä¢ Headquarters: Joranda in Orissa.

The Paramahansa Mandali

‚Ä¢ Founded by Dadoba Panderung and Bal Shastri Jambhekar of Maharashtra in 1849.

‚Ä¢ Dadoba in his book Dharma Vivechan, outlined 7 principles of this movement.

‚Ä¢ The Paramahamsa Mandali meets in secret usually.

Social Movements

Seva Sadan

‚Ä¢ The Parsi social reformer Behramji M. Malabari founded this Seva Sadan in 1885.


Servants of India Society

‚Ä¢ Founded in 1915 by Gopala Krishna Gokhale.

Indian (National) Social Conference

‚Ä¢ Founded by M.G. Ranade and Raghunath Rao.

‚Ä¢ It was the social reform cell of the Indian National Congress.

‚Ä¢ First session was held in Madras in Dec 1887.

‚Ä¢ It launched the famous ‚ÄúPledge Movement‚Äù to inspire people to take an oath to prohibit child marriage.

Social Service League

‚Ä¢ Founder: Narayan Malhar Joshi, a leading member of the Servants of India Society in 1911

‚Ä¢ Objective: to collect and study social facts and discuss social problems with a view to forming public opinion on questions of social service.

Seva Samiti

‚Äè¢ Founded by a member of the Senrvants of India Society, Hridayanath Kunzru.

‚Ä¢ Founded in 1914 at Allahabad.

‚Ä¢ Objective: to organize social service during natural disasters.

Lokahithawadi

‚Ä¢ Gopala Hari Desmukh popularly known as ‚ÄòLokahithawadi‚Äô.

‚Ä¢ He was a judge and a member of the Governal-General‚Äôs Council in 1880.

‚Ä¢ He attended te Delhi Darbur in 1876 wearing handspun khadi.

‚Ä¢ He urged the people to be self-reliant and seek Western learning.




Rahanumai Mazdayasanan Sabha (Religious Reform Association)

‚Ä¢ Dadabhai Naoroji, J.B. Wacha, S.S. Bengali and Naoroji Furdonji founded this organisation in 1851.

‚Ä¢ Objective: the re-generation of the social condition of the Parsis and the restoration of the Zoroastrian religion to its pristine purity.

‚Ä¢ Rast Goftar (Voice of Truth) was its weekly organ.

‚Ä¢ First conference was held in 1890.

Anti Untouchable Movements

Aravipuram Movement

‚Ä¢ Launched by Sri Narayana Guru on Shivaratri day of 1882 and consecrated an idol of Shiva at Aravipuram.

‚Ä¢ Sri Naryana Guru was born in a low-caste Ezhava family, had studied Sanskrit, Malayalam, Tamil and astrology.

‚Ä¢ Aravipuram Prashita was a historic event.

‚Ä¢ On the wall of the temple Sri Narayana Guru inscribed the words: ‚ÄúDevoid of the dividing walls of caste or race, or hatred of rival of faith, we all live here in brotherhood‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ Sri Narayana Dharma Paripalana Yogam (Society for the Propagation of Sri Narayana Guru‚Äôs Tenets).

‚Ä¢ Two new leaders, Dr. Palpu and Kumaran Asan joined him.

‚Ä¢ Dr. Palpu was the first Ezhava to receive education in Western medicine.

‚Ä¢ Kumaran Asan was a well-known writer and poet.

Temple Entry Movement

‚Ä¢ The avarnas or members of depressed classes in various parts of South India.

‚Ä¢ In Kerala, Sri Narayana Guru, N. Kumaran Asan and T.K. Madhavan led the movement.

‚Ä¢ After 1924, the anti-untouchability programme became a part of the Gandhian constructive programme.

‚Ä¢ In Nov 1936, the Maharaja of Travancore issued a proclamation throwing open all government-controlled temples to all Hindus irrespective of caste.

Nair Service Society

‚Ä¢ Powerful Nair leaders: K. Ramakrishna Pillai and Mannath Padmanabha Pillai.

‚Ä¢ Mannath Padmanabha Pillai founded the Nair Service Society in 1914 in Travencore.

Satya Shodhak Samaj

‚Ä¢ Founded in 1873 by Jyotiba Phule.

‚Ä¢ His book was Gulaamgiri (1872).

Bahujana Samaj Movement

‚Ä¢ Maharaja (Shahu) of Kolhapur supported this movement.

‚Ä¢ Objective: creating an anti-Congress front against Bal Gangadar Tilak.

‚Ä¢ After 1919, Baskar Rao Jadhav claimed to speak for the Bahujan Samaj.

‚Ä¢ From 1920 Mukundrao Patil began to publish a Satyashodhak paper, Din-Mitra.

‚Ä¢ The Satyashodhak message was spread in the countryside through tamasha ‚Äì the folk drama tradition of Maharashtra.

Praja Mithra Mandali

‚Ä¢ This was an anti-Brahman platform founded by a Madras-based politician, C.R. Reddy.

‚Ä¢ Earlier in 1905-06, a Vokkaliga Sangha and a Ligayat Education Fund Association were founded in Karnataka.

Sikh Movements

The Nirankari Movement

‚Ä¢ Founded in the 1840s by Baba Dayal Das, who emphasised the worship of god as nirankar (formless god).

‚Ä¢ Shabad means preaching of the guru.

‚Ä¢ Hukmnamas ‚Äì injunctions.

The Namdhari Movement

‚Ä¢ This was an offshoot of Kuka movement in Punjab, founded by Balak Singh.

‚Ä¢ Balak Singh‚Äôs followers saw in him a reincarnation of Guru Govind Singh.

‚Ä¢ In 1857, Balak Singh‚Äôs disciple Baba Ram Singh formally inaugurated the Namdhari movement.

‚Ä¢ Namdharis dressed in white, with a white turban.

‚Ä¢ The Namdharis were staunch opponents of the foreign rule (British rule).

‚Ä¢ In July 1872, sixty-five Namdharis were arrested and executed.

‚Ä¢ Baba Ram Singh was also arrested and exiled to Burma, where he died in 1885.

The Singh Sabha

‚Ä¢ Thakur Singh Sandhawalia and Giani Gian Singh founded the Singh Sabha of Amritsar on Oct 1, 1873.

‚Ä¢ Objectives:
1. To restore Sikhism to its prishtine purity.

2. To publish historical religious books and periodicals

3. To propagate knowledge using Punjabi.

4. To involve Englishmen in the educational programme of the Sikhs.

Lahore Singh Sabha

‚Ä¢ First meeting in 1879.

‚Ä¢ The Lahore Sabha was even more democratic than the Amritsar Sabha and accepted members of all castes including untouchables.

‚Ä¢ In 1880, a General Sabha was established inAmritsar, which was renamed the Khalsa Diwan, to provide a central organisation for all Singh Sabhas.

Gurudwara Reform Movements

‚Ä¢ Before 1920, the Sikh Gurudwaras were governed by the Udasi Sikh mahants.

‚Ä¢ Mahants issued a hukamnama (injunction) against the Ghadarites.

‚Ä¢ Mahants honoured General Dyer, the butcher of Jallianwalabagh massacre, with a saropa.

‚Ä¢ The Gurudwaras came under the control of an elected committee known as the Shiromani Gurudwara Prabandhak Committee (SGPC) in 1920.

‚Ä¢ The movement turned into the Akali movement.

Movements for the Emancipation of Women

Individual Activists

‚Ä¢ Raja Ram Mohun Roy worked for the abolition of sati.

‚Ä¢ Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar championed female education, supporter of widow remarriage, and opponent of polygamy.

o His efforts led to the passing of the Hindu Widow Remarriage Act in 1856.

o He opened a number of schools for girls in Bengal and was closely associated with the Hindu Kanya Vidyalaya founded by J.E.D. Bethune.

‚Ä¢ Kandukuri Vereshalingam Panthulu published Viveka Vardhani.

o Opened his first girls‚Äô school in 1874.

o In 1878 lauched an anti-nautch movement (against hiring of dancing girls for celebrations).

‚Ä¢ Mahadev Govind Ranade and his wife Ramabai.

o He founded the National Social Conference.

o She founded the Sharda Sadan, a school for widows in Bombay at Mukti, near Pune.

o Her greatest legacy was her effort, the first in India, to educate widows.

‚Ä¢ Swami Dayananda Saraswathi encouraged female education and widow remarriage and condemned child marriage, dowry and polygamy.

‚Ä¢ Rai Salig Ram (also known as Huzur Maharaj), of the Radhaswami sect, advocated female emancipication in his work, Prem Patra.

‚Ä¢ The Parsi social reformer Behramji Malabari, captured the attention of British people with his aricles in The Times (of London) on the evils of child marriage and the tragedy of enforced widowhood for young women.

‚Ä¢ Khwaja Altaf Hussain Hali, Shaikh Muhammad Abdullah and Begum Rokeya Sakhawat Hossain worked for the education of Muslim girls.

‚Ä¢ Dhondo Kesav Karve encouraged widow remarriage and he founded the female school and widow homes in Pune.

o He also founded the first Indian women‚Äôs university in 1916.

‚Ä¢ Gangabai (popularly known as Mataji Maharani Tapaswini) was a Brahman women of the Deccan, who settled down in Calcutta with a mission to promote female education.

‚Ä¢ Gangabai Founded the Mahakali Pathshala in Calcutta in 1893.

‚Ä¢ Sister Subbalakshmi was the first Hindu widow in the Madras Presidency to study for her graduation.

o She opened widow homes, female schools and an institution for teacher training.

o She opened ICC House, a school for child widows up to the age of 18 and Sharada Vidyalaya, a high school and boarding school for adult widows.

o She closely associated with the Women‚Äôs India Association and the All-India Women‚Äôs Conference.

Associations for Women

‚Ä¢ The Bharat Mahila Parishad was a part of the National Social Conference to provide a forum for the discussion of social issues.

‚Ä¢ The Arya Mahila Samaj founded by Ramabai, wife of M.G. Ranade, to provide a support network for newly educated women.

‚Ä¢ The Stri Zarthosti Mandal (Parsis Women‚Äôs Circle) served as a training ground for women.

‚Ä¢ The Bharat Stree Mahamandal founded by Sarladevi Choudarani at Allahabad in 1910. It was the first permanent association of Indian women.

‚Ä¢ The Women‚Äôs Indian Association founded by an Irish feminist and theosophist, Dorothy Jinarajadasa, in 1915.

o Annie Besant became  its first President.

o This association sent a delegation to the Secretary of State, Montagu, to grant franchise for woman.

o Its journal: Stri Dharma

The National Council of Women for India

‚Ä¢ This was an all-India organisation established in 1925, affiliated to the International Council of Women.

‚Ä¢ Mehribai Tata (wife of Dorab Tata) played key role in its advancement.

All India Women‚Äôs Conference (AIWC)

‚Ä¢ The AIWA first met at Pune in Jan 1927, through the efforts of Mararet Cousins.

‚Ä¢ In 1941, the AIWC established its quarterly journal Roshni, and in 1946 setup a central office.

‚Ä¢ The AIWC created a great deal of public opinion in favour of the Child Marriage Rstraint Act or Sharda Act.

‚Ä¢ Muthulakshmi Reddy, the first woman legislator, was appointed to the Madras Legislative Council in 1927.

Islamic Reform Movements

Anjuman-i-Himayat-i-Islam

‚Ä¢ Anjuman-i-Himayat-i-Islam founded in Lahore in 1866 by Muhammad Shafi and Shah Din, both followers of Sayyid Ahmad Khan, the founder of the Aligarh movement.

‚Ä¢ In 1869, the Anjuman-i-Islamiyah was organisation in Lahore to teach Muslim youths the principles of Islam and elements of Western education.


Ahl-i-Hadith

‚Ä¢ The death of Saiyid Ahmed Raebarelwi, the founder of the Wahabi movement in India, divided his followers into two groups.

‚Ä¢ Radical group considered Sayid Ahmed Raebarelwi as the imam-i-mahdi.

‚Ä¢ Moderate group leader was Saiyid Nazir who didn‚Äôt regard Saiyid Ahmed as mahdi and his concept of jihad and founded the Ahl-i-Hadith, a branch of Tariqah-i-Muhammadiyah.

‚Ä¢ The leaders of Ahl-i-Hadith rejected Sufism and condemned polytheism.

Titu Mir‚Äôs Movement

‚Ä¢ Mir Nithar Ali, popularly known as Titu Mir, was an ardent follower of Sayid Ahmed Raebarelwi.

The Fara‚Äôidi Movement

‚Ä¢ Founded by Haji Shariat Ullah influenced by the teachings of Shah Wali Ullah and the doctrines of al-Wahab of Saudi Arabia.

‚Ä¢ Haji Shariat Ullah called for return to fara‚Äôid (the obligatory duties of Islam) such as daily prayers (namaz), fasting in Ramzan, paying charities (zakat) and pilgrimage to Mecca (Haj).

‚Ä¢ Under Haji‚Äôs son Dudu Miyan, from 1840 onwards, this movement became revolutionary.

Ta‚Äôaiyuni Movement

‚Ä¢ An offshoot of Wahabi movement, founded by Maulana Karamat Ali, who sailed the rivers of Bengal and Assam for nearly 40 years in a flotilla.

‚Ä¢ Ta‚Äôaiyuni movement didn‚Äôt agree with the Fara‚Äôidis view that India under the British rule was dar-ul-harb or enemy territory.

‚Ä¢ dar-ul-aman means a land of peace.

‚Ä¢ dar-ul-islam means a Islamic territory.




Sir Syed Ahmad Khan and Aligarh Movement

‚Ä¢ His articles in Tahzib-al-Akhlaq, which he started in 1870.

‚Ä¢ Aligarh was the centre of his activities.

‚Ä¢ The range of his activities is known as the Aligarh movement.

‚Ä¢ He founded the Aligarh School on May 24, 1875, on the birth anniversary of Queen Victoria. This school was upgraded in 1877 to a college and named Mohammedan Anglo-Oriental College, the forerunner of the Aligarh Muslim University.

‚Ä¢ In 1887, when Badr-ud-din Tyabji was elected President of the Indian National Congress, Syed Ahmad Khan emerged actively in opposition to it.

Ahmadiya Movement

‚Ä¢ Fouded by Mirza Ghulam Ahmad of Qadiyan in 1889.

‚Ä¢ In 1889 he claimed to be masih (messiah) and mahdi, and later also to be an incarnation of the Hindu god Krishna and Jesus returned to earth.

‚Ä¢ The Ahmadiyas opposed jihad or sacred war against the non-Muslims.

Deoband Movement

‚Ä¢ The Islamic Seminary at Deoband was founded in 1867 by two theologians, Muhammad Qasim Nanautavi and Rashid Ahmad Gangohi.

‚Ä¢ Rashid Ahmad Gangohi advised the Muslim community in India to cooperate with the Congress in its activities.

‚Ä¢ Supporter of the Deoband school Shibli Numani. He founded the Nadwad-i-Ulama and Dar-ul-Uloom in Lucknow in 1894-96.

Social Reforms in the 19th Century

‚Ä¢ One of the earliest social reforms carried out through legislatiogn was the abolition of Sati in 1829.

‚Ä¢ The practice of killing infant girls was prohibited in British India by Regulation VI of 1802.

‚Ä¢ The Hindu Widow Remarriage Act, 1856.

‚Ä¢ A Widow Remarriage Association was started in Bombay in 1866.

‚Ä¢ Prof. D.K. Karve founded the Widows‚Äô Home in Poona in 1896.

‚Ä¢ Keeping slaves or trafficking in them became an offence under the Indian Penal Code (IPC), enacted in 1860.

‚Ä¢ The Brutal custom of ‚Äúhook-swinging‚Äù was suppressed in 1865.

‚Ä¢ Another act passed in 1872, abolished polygamy and marriage of minor girs (below 14 years) and sanctioned inter-caste marriages and remarriage of widows.

‚Ä¢ Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar opened nearly 35 girls‚Äô schools in 1857-58 in Bengal.

‚Ä¢ Prof. Karve founded several educational institutions in Maharashtra, the most notable being India‚Äôs first Women‚Äôs University in Bombay in the early 20th century.

