‚Ä¢ Caste Disabilities Removal Act of 1850 and Special Marriage Amendment Act of 1872 helped undermine the edifice of caste.

‚Ä¢ As far back as 1897 K. Ranga Rao started schools in Mangalore for the free education of lower castes.

‚Ä¢ In 1898, the Prarthana Samaj of Bombay started the Depressed Classes Mission Society of India in Bombay as an independent association to organize educational facilities for lower castes.

‚Ä¢ In 1909, the Depressed Classes Mission Society of Madras was launched.

Sankritisation Movements

‚Ä¢ The Chamars of Jaunpur embrassed the Siva-Narayana sect and tried to elevate their status by imitating Brahmanical forms.

‚Ä¢ The untouchable Pallars of northern Tamilnadu similarly claimed a Kshtriya status from 1871 onwards.

‚Ä¢ Ezhavas of Kerala, attacked the Brahmin domination, demanded the entry into temples and tried to ‚Äòsanskritise‚Äô some of their customs.

‚Ä¢ In Tamilnadu, the Nadars, who were the untouchable toddy-tappers, developed into a merchantile community and claimed Kshtriya status.

‚Ä¢ The Mahars of Maharashtra claimed Kshatriya origin.

Jyotiba Phule‚Äôs Movement

‚Ä¢ He started this movement in 1870s.

‚Ä¢ His books:
1. Gulaamgiri (1872)
2. Sarvajanik Satyadharma Pustak

‚Ä¢ His organization: Satya Shodhak Samaj, proclaimed the need ‚Äúto save the lower castes from the hypocritical Brahmins and their opportunistic scriptures‚Äù

‚Ä¢ The Satya Shodak Samaj was founded on Sept 24, 1873.

‚Ä¢ Mahars came under the influence of an ex-army man, Gopal Baba Walankar, claimed Kshtriya status.

Shri Narayana Dharma Paripalana Movement Yogam (SNDPY) Movement

‚Ä¢ The untouchable Ezhvas or Iravas of Kerala.

‚Ä¢ Leader: Shri Narayana Guru.

‚Ä¢ He formed the SNDPY in 1902-03.

‚Ä¢ This organisation‚Äôs objective was to give temple entry right to the untouchables.

‚Ä¢ SNDPY was influenced by Gandhian nationalism under their leader T.K.Madhavan.

‚Ä¢ The Adi-Andhra Dalits in Kerala were also influenced by SNDPY.

‚Ä¢ The untouchable poor peasants of Faridpur, called Namshudras (loyalists to the British government and against the national movement).

Adi Movements

‚Ä¢ Adi movements from the 1920s onwards there was a rise of dalit movements.

‚Ä¢ Adi-Dravida movement in Tamilnadu

‚Ä¢ The Adi-Andhra movement in Andhra and Kerala, which held its first conference in 1917.

‚Ä¢ The Adi-Karnataka movement.

‚Ä¢ The organisation of Purayas and Cherumans in Kerala.

‚Ä¢ The Adi Hindu movement, mainly centred around Kanpur in UP.

Indian National Congress and Harijan Movements

‚Ä¢ All-India meetings were held under the auspices of the Bombay Presidlency Social Reform Association in 1910, for improvement in the condition of untouchables.

‚Ä¢ The Indian National Congress at that time didn‚Äôt have social reform in its agenda, but in 1917, after the first Depressed Classes Conference was organized in Bombay, and the dalits and non-Brahmins made proposals for separate electorates, the Congress reversed its policy of excluding social reform from its agenda.

‚Ä¢ The first All-India Depressed Classes Conference was held in March 1918, issued an All-India Anti-Untouchability Manifesto.

‚Ä¢ In 1922, Indian National Congress appointed a committee ‚Äúto formulate a scheme embodying practical measures o be adopted for bettering the condition of so-called untouchables‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ In 1923, Congress again passed a resolution requesting the All-India Hindu Maha Sabha also to take up this matter and make efforts to remove this evil from the Hindu community.

‚Ä¢ In 1931, the Karachi Congress Session propounded a program of fundamental rights which called for equal access for all to public employment etc.

‚Ä¢ Mahatma Gandhi began a fast unto death on the separate electorate issue on September 20, 1932 and was able to secure an agreement between the caste Hindus and untouchables‚Äô leaders through the Poona Pact signed on September 24, 1932.

‚Ä¢ On September 25, 1932 a Conference of the Hindus at Bombay passed a resolution ‚Äúthat henceforth, amongst Hindus, no one shall be regarded as an untouchable by reason of his birth‚Äù.

‚Ä¢ Ranga Iyer introduced a bill in the Central Legislature on the subject of temple entry.

‚Ä¢ Baroda and Travancore States proclaimed temple entry in 1933 and 1936 respectively.

‚Ä¢ Mahatma Gandhi started All-India Anti-untouchability League or Harijan Sevak Sangh in September 1932.

‚Ä¢ In 1933, Mahatma Gandhi founded the weekly Harijan.

‚Ä¢ Mahatma Gandhi went on a 12,500 miles ‚ÄúHarijan Tour‚Äù between 1933 and August 1934.

‚Ä¢ The Congress governments of Bombay and Madras passed temple entry bills.

‚Ä¢ Free education for the Harijans from the primary classes onwards, was introduced by the Central Provinces and Bihar Congress governments.

‚Ä¢ Self respect movement in Tamilnadu turned radical.

Dr. Bhimrao Ramji Ambedkhar and his Depressed Classes Movement

‚Ä¢ He belonged to the untouchable Mahar caste.

‚Ä¢ In 1924 Ambedkhar founded the Depressed Classes Institute (Bahishkrit Hitkarini Sabha) in Bombay.

‚Ä¢ In 1927, he started a Marathi fortnightly, Bahishkrit Bharat.

‚Ä¢ He established the Samaj Samta Sangh in 1927.

‚Ä¢ In December 1927 he led the Mahad Satyagraha to establish the rights of untouchables to draw water from public wells and tanks.

‚Ä¢ He also organized temple entry movements like the Parvati temple Satyagraha of 1928 and the Kalasam temple Satyagraha of 1930-35.

‚Ä¢ There were similar Satyagrahas in Kerala, such as the Vaikom temple road Satyagraha of 1924-25 and the Guruvayoor Satyagraha of 1930-32.

‚Ä¢ In 1942, Ambedkar formed the Scheduled Caste Federation.

‚Ä¢ The Scheduled Caste Federation then launched Satyagrahas in Bombay, Poona, Lucknow, Kanpur and Wardha, demanding that the Congress make known its proposals to dalits.

‚Ä¢ In the 1950s, Ambedkhar embraced Buddhism.

Backward Caste Movements

‚Ä¢ Strongest in South and West India.

‚Ä¢ In North and East India,
The Kurmis and Yadavas of Bihar,
The Kolis of Gujarat,
The Kaibarttas of West Bengal,
The Jats of Rajasthan and Punjab,
The Telis of Orissa,
And even the high-castes Kayasthas of UP and Bihar followed the path of Sanskritisation in the first quarter of the 20th century.

‚Ä¢ Kaibarttas of Midnapur began calling themselves Mahishayas and started a Jati Nirdharni Sabha in 1897 and a Central Mahishaya Samiti.

‚Ä¢ Brahmins ‚Äì who accounted for 3.2% of the Madras Presidency‚Äôs population, but formed about 70% of Madras University graduates between 1870 and 1918, held about 72.6% of the district Munsifs posts in 1912.

‚Ä¢ The Justice Movement launched in 1915-16 byt C.N. Mudaliar, Dr. T.M. Nair and P. Thyagaraja Chettiar in Madras Presidency.

‚Ä¢ They made non-Brahmin Manifesto in December 20, 1916.

Anti-Brahmin Movements

‚Ä¢ Vokkaligas and Lingayats of Mysore state, Nairs of Travencore state with leaders like Ramakrishna Pillai.



Justice Party Movement

‚Ä¢ November 20, 1916, Dr. T.M. Nair, Sir Pitti Theagaraja Chettiar and the Raja of Panagal came together to form the South Indian Liberal Federation (SILF).

‚Ä¢ SILF soon launched a newspaper called Justice.

Self-Respect Movement

‚Ä¢ E.V. Ramaswami Naicker, popularly known as Periyar.

‚Ä¢ Periyar lauched the Self-Respect Movement in 1925.

‚Ä¢ His journal: Kudi Arasu.

‚Ä¢ At the Salem Conference in 1944, the Justice Party was renaed as Dravida Kazhagam.

‚Ä¢ Preiyar came up with the concept of Dravidanadu.

‚Ä¢ When Periyar‚Äôs marriage to Maniammai, a woman much younger to him, sparked a controversy, some leading lights of the Dravida Kazhagam lead by C.N.Annadurai walked out and formed the Dravida Munnetra Khazhagam (DMK) in 1949, and 3 years later DMK decided to enter electoral politics.

‚Ä¢ Begar ‚Äì forced labour.

‚Ä¢ The Alurs (Yadav) and Kurmis of Bihar opposed the begar system in the decade 1910-20.

‚Ä¢ The Alurs refused to sell cow-dung, cattle, curd and milk to land-owning upper caste at concessional rates.

Reforms by the Maharaja of Kolhapur

‚Ä¢ Reforms to uplift the lower caste came from a member of the ruling class ‚Äì the Maharaja of Kolhapur, in the 1920s.

‚Ä¢ He trained non-Brahmins to perform the Vedic ceremonies and rituals.

‚Ä¢ He also reserved 50% of the civil service posts in his state for non-Brahmins.

‚Ä¢ The Maharaja went along with the British who wanted to put Kolhapur against Tilak ‚Äì led Chitpavan Brahmin nationalists.

‚Ä¢ Bhaskar Rao Jadhav‚Äôs non-Brahmin party was bitterly hostiled to the Congress after 1919.

PEASANT MOVEMENTS

‚Ä¢ The Champaran and Kaira Satyagrahas under the leadership of Mahatma Gandhi in 1918.

‚Ä¢ Under colonial India, essentially 3 types of agrarian zones were created. These were:
1. Zamindari areas of Bengal and Taluqdari areas of UP.
nazarana - illegal dues
begar - forced labour
2. Ryotwari areas in madras presidency, where the government itself acted as the landlord.
3. Tribal zones

Some Important Peasant Uprising and Movements

Faqir and Sanyasi Rebellion

‚Ä¢ In Bengal, a large number of uprooted and homeless people joined Hindu or Muslim groups of religious medicants, known as Sanyasis or Faqirs who formed large communities and earned their livelihood from beggary.

‚Ä¢ By 1772, there was a great Sanyasi rebellion and encompassing a wide belt from Rangpur to Dakha.

‚Ä¢ Leader: Manju Shah Fakir.

Indigo Riots (1859‚Äì60)

‚Ä¢ In eastern India, in 1860, the terribly oppressed indigo peasants launched ‚Äúnon-cultivation of indigo‚Äù movements.

‚Ä¢ Began with the ryots of Govindpur village in Nadia district.

‚Ä¢ Support by the intelligentsia like Harish Chandra Mukherji, editor of Hindoo Patriot.

‚Ä¢ Complete Hindu-Muslim unity existed.

‚Ä¢ The same story was repeated in 1867-68 in Champaran (Bihar).



Deccan Riots (1874-75)

‚Ä¢ The cotton boom provided some prosperity to the peasants in the early 1860s disappeared overnight with the ending of the American civil war in 1864.

‚Ä¢ Beginning with Sirur taluk in December 1874, by May-Sept 1875, the anti-Sahukar (money-lender) Deccan riots affected 33 places in 6 taluks.

‚Ä¢ The Government passed the Agriculturists‚Äô Relief Act, 1879 which imposed restrictions on alienation of peasants‚Äô land and on the operations of the Civil Procedure Code.

‚Ä¢ Consequently, the peasant could not be arrested and sent to civil jail for failure to pay debts.

Revolt of the Ramosis

‚Ä¢ The Ramosis of Maharashtra once served in the inferior ranks of police in the Maratha administration.

‚Ä¢ Chittur Singh, who revolted in Satara in 1822 as a protest against heavy assessment, gathered these Ramosis under his banner.

‚Ä¢m In 1825, chronic scarcity in the Deccan further distressed them and they broke into revolt in 1826 under the leadership of Umaji.

‚Ä¢ British government recruited them as hill police.

Wasudeo Balwant Phadke‚Äôs Uprising

‚Ä¢ Wasuadeo Balwant Phadke raised a force of Ramosi peasants.

Pabna Agrarian Unrest

‚Ä¢ In the Permanent Settlement Areas of East Bengal (now in Bangladesh).

‚Ä¢ In reaction to this high-handedness of the zamindars the peasants of a number of districts of East Bengal launched a movement between 1870 and 1885.

‚Ä¢ The main form of resistance was legal and was generally peaceful.

‚Ä¢ The 3 principal leaders of the League were Shah Chandra Roy, Shambhu Pal and Khoodi Mollah.

‚Ä¢ The peasant discontent smouldered till the Bengal Tenancy Act of 1885.

Pagal Panthis Uprising

‚Ä¢ Its memberscame mostly from the primitive tribes, Hajong and Garo, living in the Mymensingh district of Bengal (now in Bangladesh).

‚Ä¢ Founder: a darvesh or a mendicant called Karam Shah, son and successor of Tipu.

No-revenue Movements

‚Ä¢ In Kamrup and Darrang districts of Assam.

‚Ä¢ Similarly in Maharashtra, after the famines of 1896-97 and 1899-1900, a number of non-payments of revenue campaigns were launched under the auspices of the Poona Sarvajanik Sabha, which had recently been captured by Tilak.

‚Ä¢ Punjab Alienation Act in 1902-03.

Moplah Uprisings

‚Ä¢ In the Malabar region, by Moplah Muslim peasants.

‚Ä¢ 22 revolts were recorded during 1836-1854.

Peasant Movements in the First Half of the 20th Century

Champaran Indigo Satyagraha (Bihar)

‚Ä¢ Forced by European planters to cultivate indigo on 3/20th of their holding - known as tinkathia system.

‚Ä¢ Persuaded by a local man, Raj Kumar Shukla, in 1917, Mahatma Gandhi offered Civil Disobedience and refused to leave when ordered.

‚Ä¢ Mahatma Gandhi ordered an inquiry, which involved touring with men like Rajendra Prasad and J.B. Kripalani.

Kheda Satyagraha

‚Ä¢ In Kheda district of Gujarat, Mahatma Gandhi went to alleviate the Kunbi-Patidar peasants‚Äô distress due to failure of crops.

‚Ä¢ With the help of leaders like Indulal Yajnik and Vallabhbhai Patel, Mahatma Gandhi toured the district.

Kisan and Eka Movements

‚Ä¢ Some active member‚Äôs of Home Rule League (like Gauri Shankar Mishra and Indra Narayan Dwivedi, with the support of Madan Mohan Malaviya) began organizing the peasants of UP on modern lines into Kisan Sabhas in 1918.

‚Ä¢ It was Baba Ramchandra, a Maharashtra Brahmin, who took the initiative to organize the peasants of Awadh against the landlords.

‚Ä¢ He had been wandering among the peasants since 1909, dressed like a Sanyasi quoting from the Ramacharitmanas to awaken them.

‚Ä¢ In June 1920, Baba Ramchandra and other tenants, from Pratapgarh and Jaunpur districts went to Allahabad and persuaded Gauri Shankar Mishra and Jawaharlal Nehru to visit the villages.

‚Ä¢ Awadh Kisan Sabha set up at Pratapgarh in Oct 1920.

Second Moplah Uprisings

‚Ä¢ Moplah were organized by the Congress and Khilafatists during the Non-Cooperation days.

‚Ä¢ The arrest of established Congress and Khilafat leaders like K. Mahadevan Nair, Gopala Menon, Yakub Hasan and P.Moideen Koya in Feb 1921 left the field clear for radical preachers.

Bardoli Satyagraha (Gujarat) in 1928

‚Ä¢ Followers of Mahatma Gandhi like the Mehta brothers, had carried out a sustained campaign since 1922.

‚Ä¢ Not only the landowning peasants of Kunbi-Patidar castes but also the low caste untouchables and tribes like Kali-paraj (‚Äòdark people‚Äô) participated in the movement.

‚Ä¢ They gave the tribals a less derogatory name of Raniparaj (‚Äòinhabitants of the forest‚Äô).

‚Ä¢ Bombay government announced an enhanced revenue by 22%.

‚Ä¢ A result of the Maxwell-Broomfield inquiry was that enhancement of land revenue in
Bardoli was reduced from 22% to 6.03%.




All-Indian Kisan Sabha

‚Ä¢ United Provinces of Kisan Sabha, founded in 1918.

‚Ä¢ The Andhra Provincial Ryots Association was start ed in 1928.

‚Ä¢ Bihar Kisan Sabha in 1929 by Swami Sahajanand Saraswathi.

‚Ä¢ The formation of the Congress Socialist Party in 1934.

‚Ä¢ The All-India Kisan Sabha was formed in April 1936 at Lucknow with Swami Shajanand as President and N.G. Ranga as General-Secretary.

‚Ä¢ The first session of the All-India Kisan Sabha was addressed by Jawaharlal Nehru. Others participants included Ram Manohar Lohia, Sohan Singh Josh, Indulal Yagnik, Jaya Prakash Narayan, Acharya Narendra Deva, Kamal Sarkar.

‚Ä¢ A Kisan Sabha manifesto was finalized and this was adopted by the Congress at Faizabad session.

‚Ä¢ The Kisan Sabha held its 2nd session along with the Faizpur Congress Session in 1932.

Peasant Movements during Indian National Congress Ministries (1937-39)

‚Ä¢ In Bengal, Kisan Sabha activities included a successful agitation against Canal Tax in Burdwan, and the Hat Tola movement in North Benga.

‚Ä¢ This was against a levy collected by the landlords from peasants at hat (weekly market).

‚Ä¢ In Punjab, Kisan Sabhas emerged in the early 1930s through the efforts of Naujawan Bharat Sabha, Kirti Kisan, the Congress and Akali acitivists.

‚Ä¢ 2 Major issues were resettlement of land revenue and increase in canal tax or water rate.

‚Ä¢ Major struggles broke out, especially after the Haripur session of the Congress in 1938, in Jaipur, Kashmir, Rajkot, Patiala, Hyderabad, Mysore, Travancore etc.

TRADE UNION MOVEMENTS

‚Ä¢ In 1877, the workers of the Empress Mills in Nagpur made a protest strike on the issue of their wage rates.

‚Ä¢ In 1875, first committee to inquire into the conditions of factory labour was appointed.

‚Ä¢ In 1890, the Indian Factory Labour Commission was appointed.

‚Ä¢ In 1890, N.M. Lokhandy established the Bombay Millhands Association.

‚Ä¢ Lokhandy‚Äôs was the first labour organisation to be formed in the country but it was not a trade union in the strict sense.

o Kamgar Hitvardhak Sabha (1909),
o Social Service League (1911),
o Amalgamated Society of Railway Servants of India (1897),
o Printers, Union of Calcutta (1905),
o The Postal Union in Bombay

‚Ä¢ Mahatma Gandhi established and developed the Textile Labour Association of Ahmedabad.

Early Trade Union Movement

‚Ä¢ The Madras Labour Union, formed in 1918 by B.P. Wadia, was the first modern trade organisation of India. It principally comprised textile workers of the Buchingham and Carnatic Mills. Soon thereafter, two unions were formed in Bombay, one in Calcutta (the Indian Seamen‚Äôs Union) and four in Madras.

‚Ä¢ Majur Mahajan, the Textile Labour Association of Ahmedabad and the B.B & C.I. Railway Employees Union.

‚Ä¢ In 1920, establishment of All-India Trade Union Congress. The first session of the Congress was held at Bombay in Oct 1920, presided over by Lala Lajapat Rai, President of the Indian National Congress.

‚Ä¢ According to the Directory of Trade Unions, 1925 the number of trade unions in 1924-25 was 167.

‚Ä¢ The Gaya session of the Congress (1922) went a step further and decided to assist the AITUC in organizing workers.

‚Ä¢ In 1926, the Indian Trade Union Act was enacted, which gave legal status to trade unions and was modelled on the British Trade Unions Act of 1906.

Left Trade Unions

‚Ä¢ Communist-dominated trade unions were founded after 1923.

‚Ä¢ As a result of the Communist influence on trade unions, ‚Äú1928 was a year of intense industrial unrest‚Äù.

All-India Trade Union Congress (AITUC)

‚Ä¢ The early leaders of the AITUC included Lala Lajpat Rai, N.M. Johsi and V.V.Giri.

‚Ä¢ In 1929, Communists succeeded in securing the approval of the AITUC to its affiliation to the Third International in Moscow. This lead to a split; the moderates, led by N.M. Joshi, left the AITUC and formed the All-India Trade Union Federation (AITUF).

‚Ä¢ Another split in the AITUC in 1931, when communists formed the Red Trade Union Congress (RTUC).

‚Ä¢ National Trade Union Federation (NTUF) was formed in 1933.

‚Ä¢ In 1936, the AITUC and NTUF calme closer together. In 1938, both held a commission session at Nagpur. Unity was finally achieved in 1940 ‚Äì 11 years after the first split ‚Äì when NTUF was dissolved and its trade unions affiliated themselves to the AITUC.

